const a = [
  {"id":392,"text":"Which of the following can cause inhibition of action potential?","explanation":"**Influx of chloride ions (Cl-)** can indeed inhibit action potentials in neurons. Chloride ions are negatively charged, and their influx into a neuron can lead to membrane **hyperpolarization**, making it more difficult for the neuron to reach the threshold for firing an action potential.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 581.","responses":[{"text":"Influx of potassium","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Influx of chloride","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Influx of bicarbonate","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Influx of calcium","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Influx of sodium","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":2758,"text":"Which of the following is the most common cause of pyogenic osteomyelitis?","explanation":"The most common cause of **pyogenic osteomyelitis** is ***Staphylococcus aureus***. This bacterium is responsible for a significant majority of cases, especially in otherwise healthy individuals.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\n*Salmonella typhi* is commonly associated with typhoid fever; it can cause osteomyelitis in patients with sickle cell disease.\r\n\r\n*Pseudomonas aeruginosa* can cause osteomyelitis, particularly in individuals with compromised immune systems or those with puncture wounds.\r\n\r\n*Mycobacterium tuberculosis* causes tuberculous osteomyelitis, which is different from pyogenic osteomyelitis.\r\n\r\n*Staphylococcus epidermidis* is a less virulent organism; it is more commonly associated with prosthetic joint infections rather than primary osteomyelitis.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 1195.","responses":[{"text":"Salmonella typhi","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Staphylococcus epidermidis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pseudomonas aeruginosa","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mycobacterium tuberculosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Staphylococcus aureus","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":5353,"text":"Which of the following is the longest muscle in the human body?","explanation":"The **longest muscle** in the human body is the **sartorius muscle**. It runs diagonally across the thigh, originating from the anterior superior iliac spine and inserting into the medial side of the tibia. The sartorius is involved in flexing, abducting, and laterally rotating the thigh at the hip joint, as well as flexing the knee.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 706.","responses":[{"text":"Pectineus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Iliacus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Psoas major","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Vastus medialis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sartorius","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":5471,"text":"Which of the following types of cells do Howship's lacunae contain?","explanation":"**Howship's lacunae** contain **osteoclasts**. These are specialized cells responsible for the resorption of bone tissue. Howship's lacunae are small pits on the surface of bone where osteoclasts are active. The osteoclasts attach to the bone surface and create an isolated environment where they can break down the bone matrix, releasing calcium and other minerals back into the bloodstream.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nChondrocytes are cells that produce and maintain cartilage tissue.\r\nOsteoprogenitor cells are precursor cells that can differentiate into osteoblasts.\r\nOsteoblasts are cells responsible for bone formation.\r\nOsteocytes refer to mature bone cells that maintain the bone matrix.","reference":"Mescher AL. Junqueira’s Basic Histology: Text and Atlas. 15th ed. McGraw-Hill Medical; 2018: 143.","responses":[{"text":"Osteoblasts","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Osteocytes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chondrocytes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Osteoprogenitor cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Osteoclasts","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":5489,"text":"Which of the following is the keystone of the medial longitudinal arch of the foot?","explanation":"The **talus head** is the keystone of the **medial longitudinal arch** of the foot. The medial longitudinal arch is composed of the calcaneus, talus, navicular, three cuneiforms, and three metatarsals. The talar head serves as the central point around which the arch is formed and provides crucial support to the structure of the foot. The tibialis anterior and posterior muscles, via their tendinous attachments, also help in supporting this arch.","reference":"Halliday NL, M C Harold, Won C Kyung. BRS: Gross Anatomy. 10th ed. Wolters Kluwer Health/Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2020: 228.","responses":[{"text":"Navicular bone","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Talus head","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Calcaneal tubercle","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Medial cuneiform bone","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Metatarsals","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5511,"text":"Injury to which of the following nerve causes winging of the scapula?","explanation":null,"reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 179.","responses":[{"text":"Long thoracic nerve","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Nerve to subclavius","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lateral pectoral nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Dorsal scapular nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Medial pectoral nerve","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5518,"text":"A football player gets hit on the lateral aspect of his knee joint, resulting in a fracture of the neck of the fibula. Which of the following nerves is most likely to be injured in this case?","explanation":"In the case of a fracture of the **neck of the fibula**, the nerve most likely to be injured is the **common peroneal nerve** (also known as the common fibular nerve). This nerve wraps around the neck of the fibula and is susceptible to injury in fractures involving this area.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nThe superficial fibular nerve is a branch of the common peroneal nerve, that supplies the lateral compartment of the leg.\r\nThe sciatic nerve is a large nerve originating from the lumbar and sacral plexus and splits into the tibial and common peroneal nerves.\r\nThe deep fibular nerve is another branch of the common peroneal nerve, that supplies the anterior compartment of the leg.\r\nThe tibial nerve is a branch of the sciatic nerve, that supplies the posterior compartment of the leg.","reference":"Drake RL. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 542.","responses":[{"text":"Superficial fibular nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tibial nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Common peroneal nerve","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Deep fibular nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sciatic nerve","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5528,"text":"What is chondroitin sulfate made of?","explanation":"**Chondroitin sulfate** is made of **N-acetylgalactosamine and glucuronic acid**. These two sugar molecules alternate in a chain to form the structure of chondroitin sulfate, a key component of cartilage.","reference":"Ferrier DR. Lippincott’s Illustrated Reviews: Biochemistry. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2020: 159.","responses":[{"text":"N-acetylgalactosamine + glucuronic acid","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"N-acetylglucosamine + iduronic acid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Glucuronic acid+ iduronic acid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"N-acetylglucosamine + glucuronic acid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"N-acetylgalactosamine + iduronic acid","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5547,"text":"Nernst equation describes the relationship of diffusion potential to which of the following across a semipermeable membrane?","explanation":"The **Nernst equation** describes the relationship of diffusion potential to the **concentration of a single ion** across a semipermeable membrane. It is used to calculate the equilibrium potential for an ion based on its concentration gradient across the membrane.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nConcentration of multiple ions: The Nernst equation is specific to a single ion. The Goldman equation, on the other hand, considers multiple ions.\r\nFacilitated diffusion: While facilitated diffusion is a type of membrane transport, the Nernst equation specifically deals with the equilibrium potential of a single ion, not the mechanism of transport.\r\nCo-transport: This refers to the simultaneous transport of two or more ions or molecules in the same direction across a membrane, which is not what the Nernst equation describes.\r\nCounter transport: This refers to the simultaneous transport of two or more ions or molecules in opposite directions across a membrane, which is also not what the Nernst equation describes.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 56-57.","responses":[{"text":"Counter transport","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Concentration of multiple ions","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Facilitated diffusion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Concentration of a single ion","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Co-transport","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5551,"text":"Against which of the following are autoantibodies produced in Lambert-Eaton syndrome?","explanation":"In **Lambert-Eaton syndrome**, autoantibodies are produced against **presynaptic calcium channels**. These autoantibodies interfere with the release of acetylcholine at the neuromuscular junction, leading to muscle weakness.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nAutoantibodies against muscle proteins are not the cause of Lambert-Eaton syndrome, although they may be implicated in other autoimmune conditions affecting muscle.\r\n\r\nAutoantibodies against acetylcholine receptors are characteristic of myasthenia gravis, not Lambert-Eaton syndrome.\r\n\r\nAutoantibodies against potassium or sodium channels are not associated with Lambert-Eaton syndrome. They may be implicated in other neurological conditions.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 1236.","responses":[{"text":"Sodium channels","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Presynaptic calcium channels","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Potassium channels","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Acetylcholine channels","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Muscle proteins","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5572,"text":"Which muscle unlocks the knee joint?","explanation":"The muscle that **unlocks the knee joint** is the **popliteus**. This muscle is responsible for initiating the flexion of the knee, allowing the leg to bend after it has been fully extended.\r\n\r\n\r\nGastrocnemius is primarily involved in plantar flexion of the ankle and also assists in knee flexion.\r\n\r\nThe plantaris is a small muscle that also assists in knee flexion and plantar flexion of the ankle.\r\n\r\nQuadriceps femoris is a group of muscles that are primarily responsible for knee extension, not for unlocking the knee.\r\n\r\nThe biceps femoris is one of the hamstring muscles, and it is involved in knee flexion and hip extension but does not unlock the knee joint.","reference":"Drake RL. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 618.","responses":[{"text":"Quadriceps femoris","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Plantaris","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Biceps femoris","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Gastrocnemius","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Popliteus","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":5573,"text":"Damage to which nerve presents as the claw hand?","explanation":"Damage to the **ulnar nerve** often presents as the **\"claw hand\"** deformity. This occurs because the ulnar nerve innervates the intrinsic muscles of the hand, and its dysfunction leads to an imbalance between the flexors and extensors, resulting in the characteristic clawing of the fingers.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nAxillary nerve: Damage to this nerve typically affects the deltoid muscle and results in difficulty abducting the arm, not in a claw hand deformity.\r\n  \r\nMedian nerve: Damage to the median nerve can result in \"ape hand\" deformity or carpal tunnel syndrome but not the claw hand.\r\n  \r\nMusculocutaneous nerve: Damage to this nerve affects the muscles in the anterior compartment of the arm, leading to weakness in elbow flexion and forearm supination, not a claw hand.\r\n  \r\nRadial nerve: Damage to the radial nerve can result in \"wrist drop,\" where the wrist and fingers cannot be actively extended, but it does not result in a claw hand.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 239.","responses":[{"text":"Radial nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ulnar nerve","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Median nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Axillary nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Musculocutaneous nerve","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5819,"text":"Cyclones are classified as which type of disasters?","explanation":"Cyclones are classified as **meteorological disasters**. They are natural events that occur due to atmospheric and weather conditions.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nTelluric and tectonic are terms that are generally associated with geological phenomena like earthquakes and volcanic eruptions, not cyclones.\r\n\r\nAn atomic explosion would be a man-made or anthropogenic disaster, not a natural meteorological event like a cyclone.\r\n\r\nTopological is not a term typically used to classify types of disasters. It is more commonly associated with the study of geometric properties and spatial relations.\r\n\r\nAccidents refer to unplanned events that result in harm or damage but are not natural disasters like cyclones.","reference":"Wang Y, Xiao F, Zhang L, Gong Z. Research on evaluation of meteorological disaster governance capabilities in mainland china based on generalized λ-shapley choquet integral. International Journal of Environmental Research and Public Health. Published April 12, 2021. Accessed August 12, 2023. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC8069057/","responses":[{"text":"Telluric and tectonic","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Accident","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Atomic explosion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Topological","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Meteorological","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":6003,"text":"In a patient, the iliopsoas is found paralyzed. Which of the following muscle will undergo hypertrophy to compensate for hip flexion?","explanation":"In a patient with **paralyzed iliopsoas**, the **tensor fascia latae** would likely undergo hypertrophy to compensate for hip flexion. This muscle assists in flexing the hip and would take on a greater role if the iliopsoas is compromised.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nVastus intermedius is part of the quadriceps group and is primarily involved in knee extension, not hip flexion.\r\n\r\nThe pectineus does assist in hip flexion, but it is not the primary compensatory muscle for the iliopsoas.\r\n\r\nThe semimembranosus is one of the hamstring muscles and is more involved in knee flexion and hip extension, not hip flexion.\r\n\r\nThe rectus femoris is part of the quadriceps group and does assist in hip flexion, but it is not the primary muscle that would undergo hypertrophy.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 725.","responses":[{"text":"Pectineus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Vastus intermedius","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tensor fascia latae","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Rectus femoris","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Semimembranosus","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":6133,"text":"Which of the following anatomical descriptions can help a surgeon to harvest a part of a great saphenous vein for grafting?","explanation":"The **great saphenous vein** passes superficial to the **fascia lata of the thigh**. This location makes it relatively accessible for surgical harvesting for coronary artery bypass, as it is not deeply situated within the tissues.","reference":"Drake RL. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 564, 595, 655.","responses":[{"text":"It lies anterior to the medial condyle of the femur","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It lies posterior to medial malleolus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It passes deep to the fascia lata of the thigh","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It originates from the femoral vein","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It passes superficial to the fascia lata of thigh","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":6193,"text":"What is the mechanism of action of methylxanthine?","explanation":"**Methylxanthines**, such as theophylline, is the **inhibition of phosphodiesterase**. By inhibiting this enzyme, methylxanthines increase the levels of cyclic AMP (cAMP), leading to bronchodilation and other effects.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nBeta-adrenergic receptor stimulation: This is the mechanism of action for drugs like albuterol, not methylxanthines.\r\nRegulation of intracellular fluoride levels: There is no known pharmacological mechanism involving the regulation of intracellular fluoride levels by methylxanthines.\r\nAlpha-adrenergic receptor stimulation: This mechanism is not associated with methylxanthines; it is more commonly seen with drugs like phenylephrine.","reference":"Karen Whalen, Radhakrishnan R, Field C. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 7th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2019: 194.","responses":[{"text":"Beta-adrenergic receptor stimulation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Alpha-adrenergic receptor stimulation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Regulation of intracellular fluoride levels","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Regulation of intracellular sodium levels","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inhibition of phosphodiesterase","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":6202,"text":"Cartilages are made up of which type of collagen fibers?","explanation":"Cartilages are primarily made up of **type 2 collagen fibers**. This type of collagen provides the tensile strength and structural integrity needed for cartilaginous tissues.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nType 1 collagen is mainly found in skin, tendon, and bone, but not in cartilage.\r\nType 6 collagen is found in some connective tissues but is not the primary collagen type in cartilage.\r\nType 4 collagen is mainly found in basement membranes, not in cartilage.\r\nType 3 collagen is found in reticular fibers and some connective tissues but is not the primary collagen type in cartilage.","reference":"Mescher AL, Junqueira LCU. Junqueira’s Basic Histology: Text and Atlas. 16th ed. McGraw-Hill; 2021: 129.","responses":[{"text":"Type 4","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Type 1","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Type 6","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Type 3","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Type 2","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":6217,"text":"During skeletal muscle contraction, when the myosin heads bind to actin, the Fenn effect occurs. Which of the following correctly describes this phenomenon?","explanation":"During skeletal muscle contraction, when the myosin heads bind to actin, the **Fenn effect** describes that the **work done is directly proportional to ATP cleaved**. In this phenomenon, the amount of mechanical work performed by the muscle is directly related to the amount of ATP that is hydrolyzed during the contraction process.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 84.","responses":[{"text":"Work done is inversely proportional to ATP cleaved","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Work done is directly proportional to ATP cleaved","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Work done is directly proportional to ATP and Mg2+ cleaved","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Work done is inversely proportional to ATP and Mg2+ cleaved","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Work done is directly proportional to  Ca2+ cleaved","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":6220,"text":"A woman comes in with the complaint of being unable to climb stairs. Which muscle is most likely to be weakened?","explanation":"The **gluteus maximus** muscle is most likely to be weakened in a woman who is unable to climb stairs. This muscle is the primary extensor of the hip and is crucial for activities like climbing stairs, standing up from a sitting position, and walking uphill.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nThe biceps femoris is one of the hamstring muscles and is more involved in knee flexion and hip extension but is not the primary muscle used for climbing stairs.\r\n  \r\nThe piriformis is involved in the lateral rotation of the hip and is not the primary muscle used for climbing stairs.\r\n  \r\nThe gluteus medius is involved in hip abduction and medial rotation but is not the primary muscle used for climbing stairs.\r\n  \r\nThe obturator externus is involved in the lateral rotation of the hip and is not the primary muscle used for climbing stairs.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 725.","responses":[{"text":"Piriformis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Gluteus maximus","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Gluteus medius","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Biceps femoris","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Obturator externus","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":6222,"text":"Collagen synthesis requires hydroxylation of lysine and proline residues. Which of the following is necessary as a cofactor for this hydroxylation?","explanation":"**Vitamin C** is necessary as a cofactor for the **hydroxylation of lysine and proline residues** during collagen synthesis. The hydroxylation process is essential for the stability of the collagen triple helix.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nVitamin B12 is primarily involved in DNA synthesis and the formation of red blood cells, not in collagen synthesis.\r\n\r\nWhile the B vitamins have various roles in metabolism, they are not specifically required for the hydroxylation in collagen synthesis.\r\n\r\nVitamin E is an antioxidant vitamin and is not involved in the hydroxylation process of collagen synthesis.\r\n\r\nVitamin A is important for vision and immune function but is not a cofactor for hydroxylation in collagen synthesis.","reference":"Ferrier DR. Lippincott’s Illustrated Reviews: Biochemistry. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2020: 47.","responses":[{"text":"Vitamin B","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Vitamin C","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Vitamin E","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Vitamin B12","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Vitamin A","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":6252,"text":"Which of the following enzymes is deficient in the Hurler syndrome?","explanation":"**Hurler syndrome** is caused by the deficiency of **alpha-L-iduronidase**. The deficiency of this enzyme leads to the **accumulation of glycosaminoglycans** (GAGs) in various tissues, causing a range of symptoms including developmental delay, skeletal abnormalities, and organomegaly.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nBeta-glucuronidase: Deficiency of this enzyme leads to Sly syndrome.\r\n\r\nHeparin sulfamidase: Deficiency of this enzyme is associated with Sanfilippo syndrome type A.\r\n\r\nIduronate-2-sulfatase: Deficiency of this enzyme leads to Hunter syndrome.\r\n\r\nN-acetyl-glucosaminidase: Deficiency of this enzyme is associated with Sanfilippo syndrome type B.","reference":"Ferrier DR. Lippincott’s Illustrated Reviews: Biochemistry. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2020: 164.","responses":[{"text":"Alpha-L-iduronidase","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Iduronate-2-sulfatase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Heparin sulfamidase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"N-acetyl-glucosaminidase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Beta-glucuronidase","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9102,"text":"What is a term used for continuous, sustained contraction with no relaxation?","explanation":"**Complete tetanus** refers to **continuous, sustained contraction with no relaxation**. In a state of complete tetanus, the muscle fibers do not relax between stimuli. This produces a sustained contraction, and individual twitches are not discernable. This state is usually the result of very rapid stimulation of the muscle and is an abnormal state of constant contraction often seen in certain pathological conditions.\r\n\r\nIncomplete tetanus involves a state where the muscle fibers partially relax between contractions but not completely, leading to a buildup of tension with each subsequent stimulation.\r\n\r\nTwitch refers to a single, quick contraction and relaxation cycle in a muscle fiber following stimulus.\r\n\r\nWave summation occurs when a second stimulus is provided before the muscle fiber has relaxed, thereby increasing the strength of the contraction.\r\n\r\nTreppe is a phenomenon where the strength of the contraction increases with each subsequent stimulus, often seen when a muscle is first used after a period of inactivity.","reference":"(1) Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 89.\r\n\r\n(2) Kwak D, Lee C, Kong I, Lee J, Choi D, Na C. Comparison of the spasmolytic effects of jakyak-gamcho decoctions derived via different extractants. Evidence-based Complementary and Alternative Medicine : eCAM. Published 2015. Accessed July 27, 2022. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4619897/","responses":[{"text":"Incomplete tetanus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Treppe","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Wave summation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Complete tetanus","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Twitch","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9103,"text":"Which nerve supplies the teres major muscle?","explanation":"The **lower subscapular nerve** innervates the teres major muscle. The **teres major** is a muscle of the upper limb and is situated in the posterior wall of the axilla. The lower subscapular nerve is a branch of the posterior cord of the brachial plexus, which also gives rise to the upper subscapular nerve and the thoracodorsal nerve. The function of the teres major includes medial rotation and adduction of the humerus, and it works in conjunction with other muscles like the latissimus dorsi.\r\n\r\nThe axillary nerve is responsible for supplying the deltoid and teres minor muscles but does not provide innervation to the teres major muscle.\r\n\r\nThe radial nerve is mainly associated with the muscles in the posterior compartment of the arm and forearm. It does not innervate the teres major.\r\n\r\nThe suprascapular nerve is involved with the innervation of the supraspinatus and infraspinatus muscles, which are part of the rotator cuff but are not connected to the function of the teres major.\r\n\r\nThe upper subscapular nerve primarily provides innervation to part of the subscapularis muscle, which is another muscle altogether and is not the teres major.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 174.","responses":[{"text":"Lower subscapular nerve","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Radial nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Axillary nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Upper subscapular nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Suprascapular nerve","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9104,"text":"What is the velocity of the action potential through the skeletal muscle?","explanation":"The **velocity of the action potential** through skeletal muscle is typically **3-4 m/s**. The speed can vary depending on various factors such as the diameter of the nerve fiber and the presence or absence of myelination, but in skeletal muscle fibers, it generally falls within this range. \r\n\r\n2-3 mm/s is too slow for skeletal muscle action potentials.\r\n\r\n2-3 m/s is generally associated with unmyelinated fibers.\r\n\r\n20-30 m/s is more typical of myelinated nerve fibers but is faster than what is generally observed in skeletal muscle.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 97.","responses":[{"text":"2-3 mm/s","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"20-30 m/s","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"2-3 m/s","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"3-4 m/s","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"1-2 m/s","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9105,"text":"A 67-year-old man develops bow legs and pain over a period of 5 years, and progressive hearing loss over a period of 2 years. Bone biopsy shows a mosaic pattern. Serum electrolyte patterns are normal. What is the patient suffering from?","explanation":"The patient is likely suffering from bone deformities, specifically a condition known as **Paget disease of bone**. The symptoms described, including bow legs, pain, and progressive hearing loss, along with the mosaic pattern seen on bone biopsy, are characteristic of Paget's disease. This condition involves abnormal bone remodeling, leading to **weakened and deformed bones**. Serum electrolyte patterns may remain normal, as the disease primarily affects bone metabolism.\r\n\r\n\r\nChalk stick fracture is often associated with certain types of fractures in conditions like ankylosing spondylitis, not with the symptoms described.\r\n\r\nHigh-output cardiac function is not directly related to the symptoms of bone pain, deformities, and hearing loss in this patient.\r\n\r\nAlthough giant cell tumor is a bone-related condition, it does not typically present with the symptoms described, such as progressive hearing loss and a mosaic pattern on bone biopsy.\r\n\r\nWhile hearing loss could be considered a neurological symptom, the primary issue in this case appears to be related to bone deformities, supported by the mosaic pattern on bone biopsy.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 1190.","responses":[{"text":"Bone deformities","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Giant cell tumor","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chalk stick fracture","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"High output cardiac function","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Neurological symptoms","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9106,"text":"Which of the following is true regarding the contents of the cubital fossa?","explanation":"The **cubital fossa** is a triangular depression located anteriorly on the upper limb, immediately superior to the elbow joint. The radial nerve is not actually in the cubital fossa but rather moves closely along its **lateral border**.\r\n\r\nThe median nerve is usually found medial to the brachial artery in the cubital fossa.\r\n\r\nContrary to the ulnar artery, the ulnar nerve is not typically located within the cubital fossa.\r\n\r\nThe superficial veins like the median cubital vein are usually superficial to the cutaneous nerves in the fossa.\r\n\r\nThe brachial artery is typically medial to the tendon of the biceps brachii in the cubital fossa.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 209, 233.","responses":[{"text":"All the superficial veins are deep into the cutaneous nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"The radial nerve is on the lateral side","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"The median nerve is lateral to the brachial artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"The ulnar nerve is on the medial side","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"The brachial artery is lateral to the tendon of biceps brachii","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9107,"text":"A gunshot wound at the axilla severely injures the posterior cord of the brachial plexus. Which of the following muscles would be affected?","explanation":"A gunshot wound at the axilla that severely injures the **posterior cord** of the brachial plexus would affect the **deltoid muscle**. The posterior cord gives rise to the axillary nerve, which innervates the deltoid muscle. Damage to the posterior cord would, therefore, impair the function of the deltoid, affecting arm abduction among other movements.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nThe pronator teres muscle is innervated by the median nerve, which is not a branch of the posterior cord of the brachial plexus.\r\n\r\nThe subclavius muscle is innervated by the nerve to the subclavius, which comes from the superior trunk of the brachial plexus.\r\n\r\nThe bicep brachii muscle is primarily innervated by the musculocutaneous nerve, which is a branch of the lateral cord of the brachial plexus.\r\n\r\nThe rhomboid major muscle is innervated by the dorsal scapular nerve, which is a branch of the cervical spinal nerves and not part of the brachial plexus.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 180-181, 193.","responses":[{"text":"Rhomboid major","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Deltoid","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Bicep brachii","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pronator teres","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Subclavius","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9108,"text":"A 35-year-old male was referred from an orthopedic out-patient department with intermittent locking of the right knee. He was evaluated with an anteroposterior and lateral view of the knee joint which showed a normal appearance of the knee joint with no loose body. Which additional view can be used to identify the loose body?","explanation":"In a patient with intermittent locking of the right knee and no loose body visible on anteroposterior and lateral views, a **tunnel view** can be used to identify the loose body. The tunnel view allows for visualization of the intercondylar notch and can help identify loose bodies that may not be visible in standard anteroposterior and lateral views.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nSkyline view: This view is primarily used to evaluate the patellofemoral joint and is less likely to reveal loose bodies in the intercondylar notch.\r\n\r\nAnteroposterior weight-bearing view: This view is often used to assess joint space and alignment but may not be the best for identifying loose bodies in the knee joint.\r\n\r\nOblique view: While this view can provide additional information, it is not specifically designed to identify loose bodies in the intercondylar notch.\r\n\r\nHorizontal beam lateral view: This is another lateral view that may not provide additional information about loose bodies in the intercondylar notch compared to the standard lateral view.","reference":"Bickle I. Normal knee radiographs with tunnel view | Radiology Case | Radiopaedia.org. Radiopaedia. Accessed August 6, 2022. https://radiopaedia.org/cases/normal-knee-radiographs-with-tunnel-view","responses":[{"text":"Anteroposterior weight bearing view","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Skyline view","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Horizontal beam lateral view","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tunnel view","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Oblique view","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9241,"text":"What is the diffusion potential that inhibits the net diffusion of a particular ion across the membrane called?","explanation":"The diffusion potential that inhibits the net diffusion of a particular ion across the membrane is called the **Nernst potential**. The Nernst potential describes the **equilibrium potential** for an ion across a membrane and represents the membrane potential at which there is no net movement of that specific ion from one side of the membrane to the other.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nThe action potential is a rapid rise and subsequent fall in voltage or membrane potential across a cellular membrane with a characteristic pattern.\r\n\r\nGraded potential refers to changes in membrane potential that are proportional to the size of the stimulus and can either be positive or negative changes.\r\n\r\nInhibitory postsynaptic potential (IPSP) is a kind of synaptic potential that decreases the likelihood of a postsynaptic action potential.\r\n\r\nPostsynaptic potential is a voltage change at receptor sites on a postsynaptic cell membrane in response to neurotransmitters, and it can be either inhibitory or excitatory.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 56-57.","responses":[{"text":"Inhibitory postsynaptic potential","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Action potential","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Postsynaptic potential","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Graded potential","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Nernst potential","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":9243,"text":"A man is referred to the outpatient department with no extension of proximal and middle phalanges of the 4th and 5th digits. He also has a thickening of palmar aponeurosis and digital slips. What is the proximal attachment of the thickening?","explanation":"The condition described, where the ring and little fingers are flexed and there's a thickening of the palmar aponeurosis, is indicative of **Dupuytren's contracture**. The muscle that attaches to the palmar aponeurosis is the **palmaris longus**. This muscle originates from the medial epicondyle of the humerus and inserts into the palmar aponeurosis and flexor retinaculum. It is involved in flexing the wrist and tensioning the palmar fascia.\r\n\r\nThe flexor carpi radialis, flexor digitorum profundus, and flexor digitorum superficialis are primarily involved in flexing the fingers and/or wrist but do not attach to the palmar aponeurosis. The flexor carpi ulnaris is also a wrist flexor but again does not attach to the palmar aponeurosis.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 159-160.","responses":[{"text":"Flexor digitorum profundus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Palmaris longus","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Flexor digitorum superficialis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Flexor policis longus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Flexor carpi ulnaris","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9244,"text":"A man’s medial superficial inguinal lymph nodes are enlarged. Where will these lymph nodes be found?","explanation":"The **medial superficial inguinal lymph nodes** would be found in the **groin area**. These lymph nodes receive drainage from various regions, including the lower abdomen and parts of the external genitalia.\r\n\r\nLymph nodes in the skin of the leg would more likely be popliteal lymph nodes, found behind the knee.\r\n\r\nDrainage from the rectal area generally goes to the internal iliac lymph nodes.\r\n\r\nWhile the penis does drain to the inguinal lymph nodes, it does not cover the full range of areas that these nodes drain.\r\n\r\nSimilar to the skin of the leg, drainage from the skin of the thigh would not specifically go to the medial superficial inguinal lymph nodes, although some drainage from the lower part of the thigh may go there.","reference":"(1) Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 695.\r\n\r\n(2) Bui T, Bordoni B. Anatomy, abdomen and pelvis, inguinal lymph node. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2022. Accessed July 28, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK557639/","responses":[{"text":"Skin of leg","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Skin of thigh","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Rectum","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Groin","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Penis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9245,"text":"Osteoclasts are bone cells with which of the following properties?","explanation":"**Osteoclasts** are housed in enzymatically etched depressions or cavities in the matrix known as resorption lacunae (or **Howship lacunae**).\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nOsteoclasts are primarily involved in bone resorption and contain numerous lysosomes and a ruffled border for this purpose, rather than a large amount of rough endoplasmic reticulum.\r\n\r\nOsteophytes are bony projections that form along joint margins, and they are not formed by osteoclasts.\r\n\r\nOsteoclasts are actually mature cells specialized for bone resorption.\r\n\r\nOsteoclasts do not typically communicate through gap junctions; rather, they are often in close contact with the bone matrix they are resorbing.","reference":"Mescher AL. Junqueira’s Basic Histology: Text and Atlas. 14th ed. McGraw-Hill Medical; 2015: 143.","responses":[{"text":"Housed as isogenous cells in lacunae","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"They communicate through gap junctions","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"They give rise to osteophytes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"They are immature cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"They contain large amount of rough endoplasmic reticulum","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9246,"text":"Which type of junction protein is not important for cell adhesion?","explanation":"**Calmodulin** is not important for cell adhesion. Calmodulin is a **calcium-binding messenger protein** that facilitates various cellular processes such as metabolism, muscle contraction, and intracellular movement, but it is not primarily involved in cell adhesion.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nIntegrins are membrane proteins that facilitate cell adhesion to the extracellular matrix and are involved in cell signaling.\r\n\r\nCell adhesion molecules (CAMs) molecules are involved in the binding of cells to each other and to the extracellular matrix, playing a role in cell adhesion.\r\n\r\nCadherin is a type of protein that is key for cell-to-cell adhesion, forming adherens junctions and playing roles in tissue development.\r\n\r\nSelectins are membrane glycoproteins that mediate interactions between cells and play roles in immune responses. They are also involved in cell adhesion.","reference":"Mescher AL. Junqueira’s Basic Histology: Text and Atlas. 14th ed. McGraw-Hill Medical; 2015: 75, 210, 219, 244.","responses":[{"text":"Calmodulin","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Cadherin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Integrins","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Selectins","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cell adhesion molecules (CAMs)","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9248,"text":"Which muscles are the flexors of the elbow joint?","explanation":"The muscles that act as the **flexors of the elbow joint** are the **biceps brachii and brachialis**. These muscles are primarily responsible for bending the elbow and are activated during elbow flexion.\r\n\r\n\r\nCoracobrachialis and brachialis - The coracobrachialis assists in flexion and adduction of the arm at the shoulder joint, not specifically at the elbow.\r\n\r\nAnconeus and brachioradialis - The anconeus aids in the extension of the elbow, not flexion. The brachioradialis is a weak flexor of the elbow but is not one of the primary flexors.\r\n\r\nBrachialis and anconeus - The brachialis is a flexor, but the anconeus is more involved in extension rather than flexion of the elbow.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 204.","responses":[{"text":"Anconeus and brachioradialis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Brachialis and anconeus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Biceps brachii and brachialis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Coracobrachialis and brachialis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9249,"text":"Skeletal muscle contraction is initiated by the neuromuscular junction. What is the first step in this process of skeletal muscle contraction?","explanation":"The first step in the process of **skeletal muscle contraction** at the neuromuscular junction is the **arrival of action potential to the axon terminal**. When an action potential reaches the axon terminal of the motor neuron, it triggers the subsequent steps that lead to muscle contraction.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nThe binding of calcium with the neurotransmitter vesicles occurs after the arrival of the action potential and the opening of calcium channels. \r\n\r\nOpening of the presynaptic calcium channel also follows the arrival of the action potential. It is essential for the release of the neurotransmitter acetylcholine.\r\n\r\nRelease of neurotransmitter acetylcholine is a subsequent step that occurs after calcium channels open and calcium binds to neurotransmitter vesicles.\r\n\r\nExcitation of the postsynaptic receptors is the final step in the sequence at the neuromuscular junction, happening after the release of acetylcholine.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 81.","responses":[{"text":"Binding of calcium with the neurotransmitter vesicles","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Arrival of action potential to the axon terminal","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Excitation of the postsynaptic receptors","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Opening of the presynaptic calcium channel","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Release of neurotransmitter acetylcholine","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9250,"text":"A patient comes to the outpatient department with a fracture of the upper part of the femur. Which of the following structures will not be affected?","explanation":"In the case of a fracture of the upper part of the femur, the **adductor tubercle** is least likely to be affected. The adductor tubercle is located on the medial side of the femoral epicondyle, which is a part of the distal end of the femur. It serves as an attachment point for the adductor magnus muscle and is not located in the upper part of the femur where fractures like this usually occur. Therefore, structures like the head and neck of the femur, intertrochanteric line, and possibly the quadrate tubercle are more prone to being affected in an upper femur fracture.\r\n\r\nNeck and head of the femur are directly part of the upper femur and are highly likely to be affected in such a fracture.\r\n  \r\nThe intertrochanteric line is also part of the upper femur and is located between the greater and lesser trochanters. It is likely to be involved in upper femur fractures.\r\n\r\nThe quadrate tubercle is a projection on the intertrochanteric crest of the femur and could be involved in upper femur fractures, though it is less commonly implicated compared to the neck or head of the femur.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 674, 676.","responses":[{"text":"Quadrate tubercle","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Head of the femur","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Neck of the femur","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Adductor tubercle","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Intertrochanteric line","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9251,"text":"Smooth muscle contraction begins with calcium binding to which of the following?","explanation":"In **smooth muscle contraction**, calcium ions play a crucial role. Upon entering the cell, calcium ions bind to **calmodulin**, a calcium-binding messenger protein. This calcium-calmodulin complex then activates **myosin light-chain kinase (MLCK)**, an enzyme that phosphorylates the myosin heads, enabling them to attach to actin and initiate contraction. The binding of calcium to calmodulin is the key initiating step that triggers the subsequent chain of events leading to smooth muscle contraction. \r\n\r\nTropomyosin is a protein that works with troponin in skeletal and cardiac muscle cells but does not bind directly with calcium in smooth muscle cells. Actin is the thin filament that interacts with myosin for muscle contraction but does not directly bind with calcium in this context. Myosin is the thick filament that pulls actin during contraction; it also does not directly bind with calcium in smooth muscle cells. Troponin is another protein complex involved in skeletal and cardiac muscle contraction but is not present in smooth muscle cells.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 104.","responses":[{"text":"Calmodulin","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Tropomyosin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Myosin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Actin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Troponin","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9252,"text":"Which nerve is damaged in a fracture of the surgical neck of the humerus?","explanation":"In a fracture of the **surgical neck of the humerus**, the **axillary nerve** is most likely to be damaged. This nerve innervates the deltoid and teres minor muscles and skin over the deltoid.\r\n\r\nThe dorsal scapular nerve is not commonly affected in fractures of the surgical neck of the humerus. The radial nerve is more commonly associated with fractures of the midshaft or distal part of the humerus. The ulnar nerve is generally not affected by fractures of the surgical neck of the humerus; it is more vulnerable in fractures around the elbow. The median nerve is also not commonly involved in such fractures; it's more susceptible to injury in the region of the elbow or wrist.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 155.","responses":[{"text":"Dorsal scapular nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Axillary nerve","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Radial nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Median nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ulnar nerve","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9262,"text":"Which of the following features of compact bone is different from that of a spongy bone?","explanation":"The feature of **compact bone** that is different from that of spongy bone is that **it has a Haversian system**. Compact bone is organized into **osteons** or Haversian systems, which are a characteristic not found in spongy bone.\r\n\r\nThe thoracic skeleton is made up of various types of bones that include both compact and spongy bones. The term \"cancellous bone\" actually refers to spongy bone, not compact bone. Cranial bones are also made up of both types of bone. Lining the medullary cavity is a specific feature of compact bone, but it does not distinguish it from spongy bone.","reference":"Mescher AL. Junqueira’s Basic Histology: Text and Atlas. 14th ed. McGraw-Hill Medical; 2015: 145-146.","responses":[{"text":"It has a Haversian system","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Thoracic skeleton is made up from this","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lines medullary cavity","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It is also called cancellous bone","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cranial bones are made up from this","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9263,"text":"What marks the end of the action potential peak?","explanation":"The **end of the action potential peak** is marked by the **closing of Na+ channels**. After the depolarization phase in which Na+ channels open and Na+ ions rush into the cell, the inactivation gates of these channels close. This halts the inward flow of Na+ ions, initiating the repolarization phase of the action potential.\r\n\r\nThe opening of Na+ channels is related to the initial phase of depolarization and not the end of the peak. Closing of Ca2+ channels and opening of Ca2+ channels are more relevant to muscle contraction and certain types of neurons but not generally to the ending of the action potential peak in most neurons. Closing of K+ channels would actually slow down the repolarization phase, which contradicts the end of the action potential peak.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 67-68.","responses":[{"text":"Opening of Na+ channels","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Closing of Ca2+ channels","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Closing of K+ channels","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Opening of Ca2+ channels","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Closing of Na+ channels","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":9264,"text":"Which of the following is a characteristic of renal osteodystrophy due to hyperparathyroidism?","explanation":"In **renal osteodystrophy due to hyperparathyroidism**, the characteristic finding is **hypocalcemia** and **hyperphosphatemia**. This occurs because the kidneys are less efficient at excreting phosphate and activating vitamin D, leading to decreased calcium absorption from the intestines. In response, the parathyroid glands secrete more parathyroid hormone to release calcium from the bones, leading to osteodystrophy.\r\n\r\nDecreased serum alkaline phosphatase is not a feature of renal osteodystrophy due to hyperparathyroidism; in fact, alkaline phosphatase levels may be elevated due to increased bone turnover. Chronic hypophosphatemia and hypocalcemia are not specific to hyperparathyroidism-induced renal osteodystrophy and could occur in various other conditions. Normal serum phosphatase and vitamin D3 levels are also not typical features of this condition.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 1191.","responses":[{"text":"Chronic hypophosphatemia and hypocalcemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Normal vitamin D3 level","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypocalcemia and hyperphosphatemia","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Normal serum phosphatase level","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Decreased serum alkaline phosphatase","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9265,"text":"Microscopically, compact bone contains an osteon or Haversian system comprising the Haversian canal and lamellae containing a matrix with collagen. Which type of collagen does compact bone have?","explanation":"**Compact bone** primarily contains **type I collagen**. This type of collagen provides the bone with its tensile strength and is the **most abundant form of collagen** in the body. \r\n\r\nType II collagen is mainly found in cartilage, not in bone. Type III collagen is typically found in reticular fibers, skin, blood vessels, and internal organs. Type IV collagen is primarily found in the basal lamina, not in bone. Type VII collagen is primarily associated with the skin, specifically in anchoring fibrils that attach the epidermis to the underlying dermis.","reference":"Mescher AL. Junqueira’s Basic Histology: Text and Atlas. 14th ed. McGraw-Hill Medical; 2015: 143, 145.","responses":[{"text":"Type VII","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Type I","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Type IV","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Type II","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Type III","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9266,"text":"A young medical student went to the outpatient department to check on a 50-year-old patient. He introduced himself as a doctor and prescribed some medicines. He was super proud of his achievement and told his teacher about it, who disapproved of his behavior. What was the reason for the disapproval of the teacher?","explanation":"The reason for the teacher's disapproval was that he **introduced himself as a doctor** when he is actually a medical student. This is a breach of medical ethics, as it involves misrepresentation of one's qualifications to a patient, which could result in harm to the patient due to incorrect or inappropriate medical advice or treatment. Medical ethics require transparency, honesty, and full disclosure of one's professional status when dealing with patients.","reference":"Dow Lecture slides: Locomotor module, Behavourial science slides, Topic: Ethics.","responses":[{"text":"He was proud on his wrong treatment","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"He did not follow the medical ethic","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"He did not explain the patient’s disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"He discussed it with his teacher","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"He introduced himself as a doctor","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":9267,"text":"An action potential arrives at a muscle. The muscle would get depolarized when which of the following ions moves through the membrane?","explanation":"The muscle would get depolarized when **Na+ (sodium ions)** move through the membrane. During depolarization, voltage-gated sodium channels open, allowing sodium ions to flood into the cell. This changes the membrane potential from a negative to a more positive value, leading to the initiation and propagation of an action potential along the muscle cell membrane (sarcolemma).\r\n\r\nCl- (chloride ions) generally contribute to maintaining the resting membrane potential but are not responsible for depolarization","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 68.","responses":[{"text":"Ca+2","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Na+","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Cl-","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"K+","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mg+2","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9268,"text":"Which of the following is a property of skeletal muscle?","explanation":"**Elasticity** is a property of skeletal muscles. Skeletal muscle fibers have the ability to return to their original length after being stretched or contracted, which is attributable to elasticity.\r\n\r\nThe latch system is a feature more commonly associated with smooth muscle, allowing them to maintain tension with low energy expenditure. \r\n\r\nRhythmicity is often seen in cardiac muscle and some smooth muscle like that in the digestive system, allowing for repetitive, rhythmic contractions. \r\n\r\nSelf-excitation is a property mainly of cardiac muscle, which can generate its own electrical impulses.\r\n\r\nSyncytium refers to a multinucleated cell structure often seen in cardiac muscle, where cells are connected by intercalated discs that allow rapid transmission of electrical impulses.","reference":"Herzog W. The problem with skeletal muscle series elasticity. BMC biomedical engineering. Published 2019. https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/32903293/","responses":[{"text":"Elasticity","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Rhythmicity","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Syncytium","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Latch system","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Self-excitation","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9269,"text":"The scapula is formed by which of the following structures?","explanation":"The **scapula** is formed by the **somatic lateral plate mesoderm**. The lateral plate mesoderm splits into somatic (parietal) and splanchnic (visceral) layers. The somatic lateral plate mesoderm contributes to the formation of the limb bones, including the scapula.\r\n\r\nSplanchnic lateral plate mesoderm is more involved in the formation of the viscera and does not contribute to the scapula. Paraxial mesoderm gives rise to the somites and subsequently muscles, dermis, and the axial skeleton but not the scapula. Neural crest cells contribute to the formation of various structures like some cranial bones and peripheral nervous system components but not to limb bones like the scapula. Axial mesoderm gives rise to structures along the body's central axis and does not form the scapula.","reference":"Sadler TW. Langman’s Medical Embryology. 14th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 80, 147.","responses":[{"text":"Neural crest cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Somatic lateral plate mesoderm","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Paraxial mesoderm","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Splanchnic lateral plate mesoderm","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Axial mesoderm","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9271,"text":"The resting membrane potential of the membrane is -90 mv. What causes the -86 mv?","explanation":"The **resting membrane potential of -90 mV** is primarily maintained by **leaky Na+ and K+ channels** along with the **Na+-K+ pump**. However, the -86 mV would specifically be attributed to the **leaky Na+ and K+ channels**. These channels allow a slow, constant passage of Na+ and K+ ions in and out of the cell, respectively. This creates an equilibrium between the inward flow of Na+ ions and the outward flow of K+ ions, which contributes to the resting membrane potential.\r\n\r\nVoltage-gated Ca2+ channels are generally not involved in maintaining the resting membrane potential; they play a more significant role during action potentials and muscle contractions. Voltage-gated Na+ channels are also more relevant to the initiation and propagation of action potentials, not the maintenance of resting membrane potential. Na+-K+ pump helps in maintaining the ion gradient, but the immediate cause of -86 mV would be the leaky channels.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 66-67.","responses":[{"text":"Voltage gated Na+ channels","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"All of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Leaky Na+ and K+ channels","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Voltage gated Ca2+ channels","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Na+-K+ pump","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9273,"text":"Which of the following is the most accurate statement?","explanation":"The upper limb buds are evident earlier than the lower limb buds. In human embryonic development, upper limb buds appear at the end of the **fourth week**, while lower limb buds appear a few days later, usually early in the **fifth week**.\r\n\r\nThe apical ectodermal ridge (AER) plays a crucial positive role in limb development and is a specialized structure requiring bone morphogenetic protein (BMP) signaling to develop.","reference":"Sadler TW. Langman’s Medical Embryology. 14th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 167.","responses":[{"text":"Upper limb buds are evident earlier than lower limb buds","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Limbs of different mammals are different","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Apical ectodermal ridge (AER) has a negative effect","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Limb buds become visible in the sixth week of development","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9274,"text":"The muscles of the posterior compartment of the thigh are attached to which of the following structures?","explanation":"The **muscles of the posterior compartment of the thigh** are primarily attached to the **ischial tuberosity**. This is the site where the hamstring muscles originate, and these muscles are responsible for hip extension and knee flexion.\r\n\r\nThe ishiopubic ramus is not the primary site of attachment for the posterior thigh muscles. The medial condyle is more involved with muscles of the leg than those of the thigh. Linea aspera is a site of muscle attachment on the femur, but it is not the primary site for muscles in the posterior compartment of the thigh.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 729.","responses":[{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Linea aspera","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Medial condyle","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ishiopubic ramus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ischial tuberosity","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":9276,"text":"After an injury to the right foot, a person cannot dorsiflex his foot. This is due to damage to which of the following nerves?","explanation":"The inability to dorsiflex the foot is most likely due to damage to the **deep peroneal nerve**. This nerve is responsible for innervating the muscles that control **dorsiflexion of the foot**.\r\n\r\nThe sural nerve is primarily a sensory nerve and has no role in dorsiflexion. The tibial nerve controls plantar flexion, not dorsiflexion. The superficial peroneal nerve is involved in eversion and some dorsal flexion, but it is not the primary nerve for dorsiflexion. The saphenous nerve is mainly a sensory nerve with no role in dorsiflexion.","reference":"Drake RL. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 625.","responses":[{"text":"Saphenous nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Deep peroneal nerve","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Tibial nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sural nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Superficial peroneal nerve","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9279,"text":"A patient has lung cancer and is told by the doctor to undergo a pulmonary biopsy and resection for treatment. The patient does not believe that he has lung cancer and does not want to undergo surgery even though the physician tells the patient about the low mortality rate of the surgery. What should the physician do?","explanation":"The physician should schedule weekly visits and encourage him to seek a second opinion. It is crucial to respect **patient autonomy** and **confidentiality**. If the patient does not believe he has lung cancer and is resistant to the idea of surgery, offering the option of a second opinion could provide additional information that might help him make an informed decision. Regular follow-up visits would also allow the physician to monitor his condition and provide ongoing advice.\r\n\r\nForcefully pushing for surgery, threatening the patient, or detaining him would be unethical and could be considered a violation of the patient's autonomy and legal rights. Informing family and relatives without the patient's explicit consent could violate confidentiality laws, depending on the jurisdiction.","reference":"Le T, Bhushan V. First Aid for the USMLE Step 1 2022. 32nd ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2022: 268.","responses":[{"text":"Give him weekly visits and encourage him to seek a second opinion","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Force him to undergo surgery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Detain him and have a meeting with the board","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inform his family and relatives","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Threaten him if he refuses to have his surgery","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9285,"text":"What type of disaster is a bushfire?","explanation":"A bushfire is classified as a **natural disaster**. It is a type of wildfire that occurs in bushland and can be caused by various natural factors such as lightning, as well as human activities. It is not specifically related to topography, tectonics, meteorology, or biology alone, although conditions in those domains can contribute to the occurrence and spread of bushfires.","reference":"(1) Sewell T, Stephens RE, Dominey-Howes D, Bruce E, Perkins-Kirkpatrick S. Disaster declarations associated with bushfires, floods and storms in New South Wales, Australia between 2004 and 2014. Scientific Reports. Published November 7, 2016. Accessed August 8, 2022. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC5098256/\r\n\r\n(2) Park K. Park’s Textbook of Preventive and Social Medicine. 25th ed. Bhanot Publishers; 2019: 855-856.","responses":[{"text":"Tectonic disaster","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Meteorological disaster","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Topographical hazard","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Biological disaster","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Natural disaster","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":9286,"text":"The posterior cords of the brachial plexus are named according to their position relative to which of the following?","explanation":"The **posterior cords of the brachial plexus** are named according to their position relative to the **axillary artery**. The naming of the cords (lateral, medial, and posterior) is based on their spatial relationship to this artery as it passes through the axillary region. \r\n\r\nThe pectoralis major and minor muscles are not used as landmarks for naming the cords of the brachial plexus. The brachial artery is also not the reference point for naming these cords.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 194.","responses":[{"text":"Axillary artery","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Brachial artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pectoralis minor muscle","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pectoralis major muscle","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9287,"text":"Which of the following does not shorten or change during muscle contraction?","explanation":"The **A-Band** does **not shorten or change** during muscle contraction. In the sliding filament theory of muscle contraction, the actin (thin) filaments slide over the myosin (thick) filaments, leading to a shortening of the sarcomere, but the length of the A-band remains constant.\r\n\r\nThe sarcomere shortens as a result of the sliding filament mechanism, leading to muscle contraction. The I-Band, which is made up of actin filaments, also shortens during muscle contraction. The H-band, which contains only myosin filaments, shortens as well. The Z-lines, which mark the boundaries of a sarcomere, move closer together, indicating the shortening of the sarcomere.","reference":"(1) Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 82. \r\n\r\n(2) Le T, Bhushan V. First Aid for the USMLE Step 1 2022. 32nd ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2022: 464.","responses":[{"text":"I-Band","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"H-band","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Z-line","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"A-Band","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Sarcomere","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9288,"text":"The collagen superfamily consists of 25 types. Which of the following is the most abundant type of collagen?","explanation":"The **most abundant type** of collagen in the human body is **type 1 collagen**. This type of collagen is found in various tissues including skin, bone, tendons, and ligaments.\r\n\r\nThe rest of the types are less abundant than type 1 collagen. Type 2 collagen is mainly found in cartilaginous tissues. Type 3 collagen is found in reticular fibers. Type 4 collagen is found in the basal lamina. Type 5 collagen is found in hair, placenta, and the surfaces of cells but is also less prevalent than type 1 collagen.","reference":"Ferrier DR. Lippincott’s Illustrated Reviews: Biochemistry. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2020: 43.","responses":[{"text":"1","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"5","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"2","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"3","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"4","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9289,"text":"For routine blood sample collection of a patient, the nurse selects a vein present superficially, in the subcutaneous tissue overlying the cubital fossa, in front of the bicipital aponeurosis. Which of the following vein is being used for venipuncture?","explanation":"The **median cubital vein** is the vein being used for blood sample collection in this patient and is superficially located in the subcutaneous tissue overlying the cubital fossa and in front of the **bicipital aponeurosis**. This vein is often chosen due to its superficial location and the ease of venipuncture.\r\n\r\nThe cephalic vein is located laterally in the arm and does not cross the cubital fossa. The axillary vein is much higher in the arm, located in the axilla (armpit), and is not used for routine venipuncture. The median vein is more distal and not typically used for routine venipuncture. The basilic vein is found medially and also does not cross the cubital fossa.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 209, 214.","responses":[{"text":"Median vein","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Basilic vein","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Median cubital vein","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Axillary vein","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cephalic vein","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9290,"text":"Which of the following is true about the brachial plexus?","explanation":"The **medial and lateral pectoral nerves** have **no cutaneous branches**. These nerves primarily supply the pectoral muscles and do not contribute to skin sensation.\r\n\r\nThe roots of the brachial plexus do not divide behind the second part of the axillary artery; they actually merge to form trunks, which then divide into divisions. The dorsal scapular nerve originates directly from the C5 root of the brachial plexus, not from the trunk. Lastly, the roots of the brachial plexus actually emerge between the anterior and middle scalene muscles, not behind them.","reference":"Drake RL. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 728, 733.","responses":[{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"The dorsal scapular nerve originates from the trunk of the brachial plexus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"The roots divide behind the second part of the axillary artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"The roots of the brachial plexus originate behind the scalene muscles","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"The medial and lateral pectoral nerves have no cutaneous branches","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":9329,"text":"A patient after recovery from the fracture of the fibula complains of inversion of the foot. Diagnosis of paralysis of peroneus longus muscle is made due to compression of the tendon of paralyzed muscle attached to which of the following?","explanation":"The tendon of the **peroneus longus muscle** is attached to the **first metatarsal and medial cuneiform**. This muscle plays a crucial role in the eversion of the foot. Paralysis of this muscle due to compression could result in an imbalance, leading to involuntary inversion of the foot.\r\n\r\nThe talus is a tarsal bone that forms the ankle joint but is not the attachment point for the peroneus longus. The cuboid is a bone in the foot but again is not the main attachment point for this muscle. The calcaneus is the heel bone and is not related to the peroneus longus muscle. The lateral cuneiform is another cuneiform bone but not the attachment point for the peroneus longus.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 750.","responses":[{"text":"Cuboid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Calcaneus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lateral cuneiform","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Talus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Medial cuneiform","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":9330,"text":"A female patient is brought to the emergency department. X-ray findings show a fracture of the femoral neck and avascular necrosis of the femoral head. This is most likely a consequence of interruption to the blood supply to the head of the femur. What is the source of blood supply to the femoral head?","explanation":"The primary source of blood supply to the femoral head is the **branches from the profunda femoris artery**. These are the **medial and lateral circumflex femoral arteries**, and they play a critical role in supplying the head and neck of the femur. Interruption to these vessels can lead to avascular necrosis of the femoral head, a serious condition that requires prompt management.\r\n\r\nThe obturator artery primarily supplies the adductor muscles and does not significantly contribute to the blood supply of the femoral head. \r\n\r\nThe femoral artery itself gives off the profunda femoris but doesn't directly supply the femoral head. \r\n\r\nThe Inferior gluteal artery supplies the gluteus maximus and is not a main supplier to the femoral head. \r\n\r\nThe tibial artery is involved in the lower leg and does not supply the femoral head.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 791.","responses":[{"text":"Femoral artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tibial artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inferior gluteal artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Obturator artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Branches from the profunda femoris artery","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":9331,"text":"Outward rotation of the leg with the knee semi-flexed is a function of which muscle?","explanation":"The **biceps femoris** brings about the **outward rotation of the leg with the knee semi-flexed**. This muscle is one of the three **hamstring muscles**, and it originates from both the ischium and the femur to insert on the head of the fibula. When contracted, it aids in knee flexion and also participates in outward (lateral) rotation of the semi-flexed knee.\r\n\r\nSemimembranosus and semitendinosus are also hamstrings, but they generally participate in inward (medial) rotation of the knee. \r\n\r\nSartorius is a long, thin muscle that runs from the pelvis to the medial side of the knee; its primary actions include flexion, abduction, and lateral rotation of the hip, but it is less involved in outward rotation of the knee when semi-flexed. \r\n\r\nGracilis is a thin muscle that runs from the pubic bone to the medial surface of the tibia; it is involved in hip adduction and knee flexion, but not in outward rotation of the semi-flexed knee.","reference":"Drake RL. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 590.","responses":[{"text":"Semitendinosus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Gracilis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Biceps femoris","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Semimembranosus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sartorius","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9332,"text":"In Paget disease, the activity of osteoblasts is determined by which of the following?","explanation":"In Paget disease, the activity of osteoblasts is best determined by **serum alkaline phosphatase**. This enzyme is released during the process of bone formation and is elevated in conditions where there is **increased osteoblastic activity**, as seen in Paget disease. It serves as an important marker to monitor disease activity and response to treatment.\r\n\r\nBone calcium and serum calcium are not specific markers for osteoblastic activity and are often normal in Paget disease. Bone alkaline phosphatase is also an indicator but is less commonly used than serum alkaline phosphatase. Serum phosphorus is not a specific marker for osteoblastic activity.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 1191.","responses":[{"text":"Bone alkaline phosphatase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Serum calcium","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bone calcium","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Serum alkaline phosphatase","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Serum phosphorus","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9333,"text":"A person is having pain and tenderness in the left ankle joint. Which structure is most likely to be ruptured?","explanation":"The **lateral ligament** is most likely to be ruptured. The lateral ligament complex of the ankle, which includes the anterior talofibular ligament, the calcaneofibular ligament, and the posterior talofibular ligament, is commonly injured in ankle sprains. These usually occur due to inversion injuries where the sole of the foot turns inward.\r\n\r\nThe medial ligament, also known as the deltoid ligament, is much stronger and less commonly injured than the lateral ligament. The posterior cruciate ligament and the anterior cruciate ligament are ligaments within the knee joint, not the ankle. Thus, they would not be implicated in ankle pain and tenderness.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 825.","responses":[{"text":"Deltoid ligament","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lateral ligament","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Anterior cruciate ligament","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Posterior cruciate ligament","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Medial ligament","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9334,"text":"A patient loses flexion and lateral rotation at the hip joint. Which muscle is injured?","explanation":"The **loss of flexion and lateral rotation** at the hip joint suggests injury to the **sartorius** muscle. The sartorius is responsible for flexing, abducting, and laterally rotating the hip. It is a long, thin muscle that runs across the upper and medial thigh, and it is involved in actions like crossing the legs.\r\n\r\nThe hamstring muscles mainly facilitate hip extension and knee flexion, rather than hip flexion and lateral rotation. Gluteus minimus primarily acts as a hip abductor. The biceps femoris is a part of the hamstring group, more involved in hip extension and knee flexion. Gluteus maximus is mainly responsible for hip extension and external rotation but is not particularly involved in flexion or lateral rotation of the hip.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 704, 723, 729.","responses":[{"text":"Hamstring","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Biceps femoris","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Gluteus maximus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sartorius","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Gluteus minimus","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9335,"text":"Full knee flexion and full hip extension cannot be achieved simultaneously due to which of the following reasons?","explanation":"The reason **full knee flexion** and **full hip extension** cannot be achieved simultaneously is due to the **shortening of the hamstrings**. The hamstrings are two-joint muscles that cross both the hip and knee joints. When the hip is extended, the hamstrings are stretched over the hip, limiting their ability to allow further knee flexion. Similarly, when the knee is fully flexed, the hamstrings are stretched over the knee, restricting their ability to permit full hip extension.\r\n\r\nShortening of the gastrocnemius, rotation of the fibula, and rotation of the tibia primarily affect ankle and knee mechanics but not the simultaneous movement of the knee and hip. Shortening of the rectus femoris could restrict hip flexion and knee extension but not hip extension and knee flexion.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 730-731.","responses":[{"text":"Shortening of the rectus femoris","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Rotation of tibia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Shortening of the hamstrings","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Rotation of fibula","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Shortening of the gastrocnemius","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9336,"text":"Which of the following organelles is characterized by the presence of cisternae and T-tubules?","explanation":"**Cisternae and T-tubules** are associated with the **sarcoplasmic reticulum** in muscle cells. The sarcoplasmic reticulum stores calcium ions and releases them to initiate muscle contraction.\r\n\r\nSmooth endoplasmic reticulum is involved in lipid synthesis and detoxification processes. The rough endoplasmic reticulum is studded with ribosomes for protein synthesis, and it also does not have cisternae or T-tubules. The sarcolemma is the cell membrane of a muscle cell. Lysosomes are involved in breaking down waste materials and cellular debris.","reference":"Mescher AL, Junqueira LCU. Junqueira’s Basic Histology: Text and Atlas. 16th ed. McGraw-Hill; 2021: 28, 198.","responses":[{"text":"Lysosomes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sarcolemma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sarcoplasmic reticulum","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Smooth endoplasmic reticulum","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Rough endoplasmic reticulum","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9337,"text":"The saphenous vein is grafted in which of the following conditions?","explanation":"The **saphenous vein** is commonly grafted in **coronary occlusive disease** for coronary artery bypass grafting (CABG). In this surgical procedure, the saphenous vein from the leg is used to create a new route around blocked coronary arteries, restoring blood flow to the heart muscle.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nFemoral hernia treatment does not use saphenous vein grafts; it involves surgical repair. Varicose veins might require removal, not grafting, of the saphenous vein. Thrombophlebitis is managed with medications like anticoagulants. Hypertension is treated with lifestyle changes and medications.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 699.","responses":[{"text":"Thrombophlebitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Femoral hernia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Varicose vein","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Coronary occlusive disease","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypertensive disease","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9338,"text":"From where are infusions mostly given into the saphenous vein?","explanation":"Infusions into the saphenous vein are typically given at the **ankle**. This location provides relatively easy access to the vein for procedures like venous cannulation.\r\n\r\nWhile technically the saphenous vein is accessible at all these points, the ankle is the most commonly used site for infusions because of its easy accessibility.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 700.","responses":[{"text":"Foot","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ankle","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"All of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Knee","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Thigh","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9634,"text":"The ventral and lateral flexor muscles of the vertebral column are derived from which of the following myotomes?","explanation":"The **ventral and lateral flexor muscles** of the vertebral column are derived from the **thoracic** myotomes.\r\n\r\nThe **cervical** myotomes give rise to muscles in the cervical region, which generally are not the primary flexors of the vertebral column. The **epaxial division** relates to the dorsal or back muscles and is not responsible for the ventral and lateral flexor muscles of the vertebral column. **Lumbar** myotomes contribute to the quadratus lumborum muscle. Finally, **sacrococcygeal** myotomes contribute to the musculature of the pelvic region and have no role in the development of the ventral and lateral flexor muscles of the vertebral column.","reference":"Moore KL, Persaud TVN, Torchia MG. The Developing Human: Clinically Oriented Embryology. 11th ed. Saunders/Elsevier; 2020: 334.","responses":[{"text":"Epaxial division","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sacrococcygeal","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Thoracic","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Lumbar","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cervical","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11711,"text":"Median nerve compression arises between the two heads of a forearm muscle. This muscle also forms the medial border of the cubital fossa. What is the name of this muscle?","explanation":"The  **pronator teres** muscle forms the **medial border of the cubital fossa** and is also responsible for the compression of the median nerve between its two heads. This muscle is a key player in forearm pronation and is situated in the anterior compartment of the forearm. Compression of the median nerve can lead to symptoms such as pain, numbness, and tingling in the areas supplied by the nerve.","reference":"(1) Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 209, 238. \r\n\r\n(2) Dididze M, Tafti D, Sherman A l. Pronator teres syndrome. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2022. Accessed April 14, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK526090/","responses":[{"text":"Brachioradialis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pronator teres","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Biceps brachii","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Brachialis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pectoralis major","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11896,"text":"A pregnant woman undergoes an ultrasound and finds out that her baby's right upper limb has not developed. It is concluded that the deformity is due to an abnormality in mesenchymal cells. Where do these abnormal mesenchymal cells belong?","explanation":"The abnormal mesenchymal cells responsible for the baby's undeveloped right upper limb belong to the **lateral plate mesoderm**. This is the layer that gives rise to limb buds during embryological development. Abnormalities in these cells can lead to limb deformities.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nThe paraxial mesoderm forms somites and is mainly responsible for the axial skeleton and skeletal muscles.\r\n\r\nIntermediate mesoderm forms urogenital structures. \r\n\r\nThe notochord serves as a basis for the development of the spinal column. \r\n\r\nThe prochordal plate is involved in the formation of the mouth and the head.","reference":"Sadler TW. Langman’s Medical Embryology. 14th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 167.","responses":[{"text":"Lateral plate mesoderm","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Intermediate mesoderm","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Paraxial mesoderm","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Notochord","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Prochordal plate","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11897,"text":"In a geriatric clinic, old people are screened for diabetes. Which type of prevention is this?","explanation":"**Secondary prevention** aims at early detection and treatment of diseases to prevent their progression. **Screening for diabetes** in a geriatric clinic falls under this category, as the goal is to **identify the disease in its early stages** and initiate appropriate management to prevent complications.\r\n\r\nPrimordial prevention focuses on averting the emergence of risk factors in the first place. \r\n\r\nPrimary prevention aims to prevent the onset of disease by controlling risk factors. \r\n\r\nTertiary prevention involves reducing the impact of the disease on patients who have already been diagnosed, preventing complications, and improving quality of life. \r\n\r\nQuaternary prevention is the set of health activities to mitigate or avoid the consequences of unnecessary or excessive intervention in the health system.","reference":"Kisling LA, M Das J. Prevention strategies. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2022. Accessed April 7, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK537222/","responses":[{"text":"Primary","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Primordial","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tertiary","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Secondary","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Quaternary","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11898,"text":"Which structure is most anterior in the popliteal fossa?","explanation":"The **popliteal artery** is the structure that is **most anterior** in the popliteal fossa. In the popliteal fossa, the arrangement from anterior to posterior (deep to superficial) is usually the popliteal artery, followed by the popliteal vein, and then the tibial nerve.\r\n\r\nThe tibial nerve is generally the most posterior structure in the fossa. The popliteal vein is usually situated between the tibial nerve and the popliteal artery. The sciatic nerve splits into the tibial nerve and the common peroneal nerve before entering the popliteal fossa, and hence, is not a structure within the fossa itself. The common peroneal nerve also diverges from the sciatic nerve and is usually found at the lateral side of the fossa.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 745-746.","responses":[{"text":"Popliteal vein","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Popliteal artery","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Tibial nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sciatic nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Common peroneal nerve","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11899,"text":"Vitamin D is required for the mineralization of bone and its deficiency in growing individuals could lead to bowing of legs and knocking of knees. What is this defect known as?","explanation":"The defect caused by **vitamin D deficiency** in growing individuals, leading to **bowing of legs** and **knocking of knees**, is known as **rickets**. Vitamin D plays a crucial role in calcium and phosphorus metabolism, and its deficiency can result in poor mineralization of the growing bone.\r\n\r\nOsteomalacia is the adult equivalent of rickets and is also due to vitamin D deficiency, but it does not result in the bowing of legs in the same way because the growth plates have already closed. Osteopetrosis is a hereditary condition characterized by dense bones, due to a defect in bone resorption. Osteoporosis is characterized by decreased bone mass and increased susceptibility to fractures. Paget disease of bone involves excessive bone resorption followed by abnormal bone formation, affecting one or multiple bones but not the entire skeleton.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 440-441.","responses":[{"text":"Paget’s disease of bone","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Osteomalacia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Osteopetrosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Rickets","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Osteoporosis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11900,"text":"While observing a knee joint, a resident orthopedist noticed a groove between the lateral epicondyle of the femur and the tibial articular surface. Which muscle is attached to this groove?","explanation":"The **popliteus** muscle attaches to the groove between the **lateral epicondyle of the femur** and the **tibial articular surface**. This muscle plays a crucial role in \"unlocking\" the knee joint by laterally rotating the femur on the tibia or medially rotating the tibia during flexion of the knee.\r\n\r\nGastrocnemius and plantaris are more related to the posterior leg and ankle movement. The biceps femoris is part of the hamstrings and is attached to the ischial tuberosity and the head of the fibula. The adductor magnus is a muscle of the inner thigh and does not interact with the lateral epicondyle of the femur in the way described.","reference":"(1) Drake RL. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 576-577.\r\n\r\n(2) Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 757.","responses":[{"text":"Gastrocnemius","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Plantaris","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Popliteus","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Adductor magnus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Biceps femoris","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11903,"text":"A person comes to the outpatient department with pain in his middle finger. The doctor finds pus present between the third and fifth metacarpals beneath the palmar aponeurosis. What is this space known as?","explanation":"The space where pus is present between the third and fifth metacarpals beneath the **palmar aponeurosis** is known as the **midpalmar space**. This is one of the anatomical divisions of the palm, separated from the thenar and hypothenar spaces, and is a common location for infections to manifest.\r\n\r\nThe thenar space is located at the base of the thumb, and the hypothenar space is located at the base of the little finger. The pulp refers to the fleshy portion of the fingers and toes, and the palm crease is not a defined anatomical space for infection.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 244.","responses":[{"text":"Pulp","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Thenar space","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Midpalmar space","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Palm crease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypothenar space","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11904,"text":"A 20-year-old man comes to the emergency department after a motorbike accident. Due to the accident, the greater trochanter of his femur is damaged. Which muscle attaches to this structure?","explanation":"The muscle that attaches to the **greater trochanter** of the femur is the **gluteus minimus**. This muscle originates from the external surface of the ilium and inserts into the greater trochanter, playing a vital role in hip abduction and stabilization during walking.\r\n\r\nThe iliacus and psoas major form the iliopsoas muscle, which is primarily involved in hip flexion and does not attach to the greater trochanter. Psoas minor is a small muscle that assists in flexing the hip and also does not attach to the greater trochanter. Gluteus maximus is the largest muscle in the gluteal region and is responsible for hip extension and external rotation, but it does not directly attach to the greater trochanter.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 723.","responses":[{"text":"Iliacus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Gluteus maximus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Psoas major","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Psoas minor","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Gluteus minimus","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":11905,"text":"A man comes to the outpatient department with chronic liver disease. On examination, it is found that his ring and little fingers are flexed and there is a thickening of the palmar aponeurosis. Which muscle attaches to the aponeurosis?","explanation":"The condition described, where the ring and little fingers are flexed and there's a thickening of the palmar aponeurosis, is indicative of **Dupuytren's contracture** that is commonly seen in patients with chronic liver disease. The muscle that attaches to the **palmar aponeurosis** is the **palmaris longus**. This muscle originates from the medial epicondyle of the humerus and inserts into the palmar aponeurosis and flexor retinaculum. It is involved in **flexing the wrist** and **tensioning the palmar fascia**.\r\n\r\nThe flexor carpi radialis, flexor digitorum profundus, and flexor digitorum superficialis are primarily involved in flexing the fingers and/or wrist but do not attach to the palmar aponeurosis. The flexor carpi ulnaris is also a wrist flexor but again does not attach to the palmar aponeurosis.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 159-160.","responses":[{"text":"Flexor digitorum superficialis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Flexor carpi ulnaris","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Palmaris longus","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Flexor carpi radialis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Flexor digitorum profundus","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11906,"text":"When the forearm is flexed such that it is 90º to the arm and, whilst keeping it in the mid-prone position, further flexing it against resistance, a muscle is made prominently visible below the elbow. What muscle is visible below the elbow?","explanation":"The **brachioradialis** becomes prominently visible below the elbow when the forearm is flexed at a 90º angle to the arm and further flexed against resistance in the mid-prone position. This muscle is specifically designed to be most effective when the forearm is in a mid-prone position and is a primary muscle involved in flexing the elbow.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nThe biceps brachii is more involved in supination and is located more proximally on the arm. \r\n\r\nTriceps brachii is mainly an extensor of the forearm and is located on the posterior side of the upper arm. \r\n\r\nTeres major is a shoulder muscle and is not located near the elbow. \r\n\r\nThe pronator quadratus is a deep muscle of the forearm involved in pronation and is not prominently visible.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 222.","responses":[{"text":"Pronator quadratus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Teres major","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Biceps brachii","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Brachioradialis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Triceps brachii","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11907,"text":"A 41-year-old patient loses sensation on the anterior and lateral sides of his thigh, down to his knee. A nerve that laterally passes under the inguinal ligament might be damaged. What could this nerve be?","explanation":"The nerve likely to be damaged, given the **loss of sensation on the anterior and lateral sides of the thigh** down to the knee, is the **lateral cutaneous nerve of the thigh** (also known as the **lateral femoral cutaneous nerve**). This nerve laterally passes under the inguinal ligament and is responsible for the loss of sensation in this patient.\r\n\r\nThe femoral nerve mainly provides sensation to the anterior thigh and medial leg but does not exclusively serve the lateral thigh. The medial cutaneous nerve primarily supplies the skin over the medial aspect of the thigh. The sciatic nerve is more related to the back of the thigh and the leg. The anterior cutaneous nerve would not be responsible for the lateral side of the thigh.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 696.","responses":[{"text":"Sciatic nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lateral cutaneous nerve","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Medial cutaneous nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Anterior cutaneous nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Femoral nerve","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11908,"text":"Pes anserine bursa is associated with insertion of which of the following muscles?","explanation":"The **pes anserine bursa** is associated with the insertion of the **sartorius, gracilis**, and **semitendinosus** muscles. These muscles converge at the anteromedial (front and inside) surface of the proximal tibia, forming the \"goose foot\" or pes anserine. The bursa serves to reduce friction between the tendon and the bone, allowing for smooth movement. \r\n\r\nThe other groups of muscles listed do not insert at the pes anserine bursa. For example, semimembranosus, semitendinosus, and bicep femoris are all hamstrings but they do not all insert at the pes anserine. Similarly, the vastus muscles are part of the quadriceps and are not related to the pes anserine bursa.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 805.","responses":[{"text":"Semimembranosus, semitendinosus, bicep femoris","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Gracilis, semitendinosus, semimembranosus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sartorius, gracilis, semimembranosus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sartorius, gracilis, semitendinosus","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Vastus medialis, vastus intermedius, vastus lateralis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11909,"text":"The unhappy triad of the knee is made up of the rupture of which of the following?","explanation":"The **unhappy triad of the knee** involves the rupture of the **anterior cruciate ligament, medial meniscus**, and **medial collateral ligament**. This injury pattern typically occurs from a lateral force applied to a planted leg, such as in certain sports injuries. \r\n\r\nPosterior cruciate ligament injuries are less common and usually not a part of this triad. The lateral collateral ligament is also usually not involved in the unhappy triad.","reference":"Drake RL. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 606.","responses":[{"text":"Anterior cruciate ligament, medial meniscus, lateral collateral ligament","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Posterior cruciate ligament, medial meniscus, lateral collateral ligament","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Medial collateral ligament, medial meniscus, lateral collateral ligament","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Posterior cruciate ligament, medial meniscus, medial collateral ligament","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Anterior cruciate ligament, medial meniscus, medial collateral ligament","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":11910,"text":"What are the strong bundles of fibers attaching the periosteum to the bone?","explanation":"The strong bundles of fibers that attach the periosteum to the bone are called **Sharpey's fibers**. These fibers are particularly numerous at sites where tendons, ligaments, and fasciae attach to the bone. \r\n\r\nCollagen fibers are the main components of Sharpey's fibers but they are not the fibers that specifically attach the periosteum to bone. Elastic fibers are more related to the flexibility and stretchability of certain tissues like the skin and blood vessels. Reticular fibers provide a supportive framework in soft tissues. Lamellar fibers are not a recognized term in this context.","reference":"Mescher AL. Junqueira’s Basic Histology: Text and Atlas. 15th ed. McGraw-Hill Medical; 2018: 143.","responses":[{"text":"Sharpey fibers","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Reticular fibers","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Collagen fibers","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Elastic fibers","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lamellar fibers","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11911,"text":"What is the change in pattern of disease which affects the level and character of mortality in a population called?","explanation":"The **change in the pattern of disease** which affects the level and character of mortality in a population is called **epidemiological transition**. This term describes a shift in the leading causes of death from infectious to chronic diseases over time, often accompanying economic and social development.\r\n\r\nDemographic transition refers to the change in birth and death rates in a population, usually from high to low, as a country develops. Level transmission and disease transmission are terms that are more related to the spread of disease rather than the change in pattern affecting mortality. Character transition is not a recognized term in this context.","reference":"McKeown RE. The epidemiologic transition: changing patterns of mortality and population dynamics. American journal of lifestyle medicine. Published July 1, 2009. Accessed July 18, 2022. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC2805833/","responses":[{"text":"Disease transmission","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Demographic transition","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Epidemiological transition","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Level transmission","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Character transition","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11912,"text":"Which artery is the most unlikely to be damaged upon injury to the snuffbox?","explanation":"The **ulnar artery** is the most unlikely to be damaged upon injury to the snuffbox. The **anatomical snuffbox** is a triangular depression found on the lateral aspect of the dorsum of the hand. It is primarily related to structures like the radial artery, cephalic vein, and the scaphoid and trapezium bones. The ulnar artery runs on the medial side of the forearm and does not pass through the snuffbox.\r\n\r\nThe **dorsalis pollicis arteries, radial artery**, and the **origin of the cephalic vein** are all structures that are actually located in or near the snuffbox and hence could potentially be injured. The dorsal carpal branch of the radial artery is also near this area. Therefore, these structures are more likely to be injured in case of trauma to the snuffbox.","reference":"(1) Drake RL. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 792. \r\n\r\n(2) Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 223.","responses":[{"text":"Dorsalis pollicis arteries","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ulnar artery","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Dorsal carpal branch of radial artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Radial artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Origin of the cephalic vein","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11913,"text":"Which of the following will not be responsible for arm abduction from 0° to 180°?","explanation":"The **intact radial nerve** is not responsible for **arm abduction from 0° to 180°**. The radial nerve primarily supplies the extensors of the wrist and does not play a role in shoulder abduction.\r\n\r\nThe trapezius muscle assists in the full abduction of the arm, especially when moving beyond 90°. Initiation by supraspinatus is correct; this muscle initiates the first 15-30° of abduction. Deltoid fibers are major players in arm abduction, especially after the first 15-30°. An intact axillary nerve is essential for deltoid function, which is a major abductor of the arm.","reference":"(1) Drake RL. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 686-687.\r\n\r\n(2) Le T, Bhushan V. First Aid for the USMLE Step 1 2022. 32nd ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2022: 454.","responses":[{"text":"Intact radial nerve","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Initiation by supraspinatus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Trapezius muscle","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Deltoid fibres","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Intact axillary nerve","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11914,"text":"A 10-year-old boy continuously complained about having pain in his navicular bone. Upon examination, the physician found a shortening of the Achilles tendon and flattened medial longitudinal arch. What deformity could be related to this?","explanation":"The symptoms described, including pain in the navicular bone, shortening of the Achilles tendon, and a flattened medial longitudinal arch, are indicative of **pes planus**, also known as **flatfoot**.\r\n\r\nClub foot is a congenital deformity involving multiple components of the foot and is typically identified soon after birth.\r\n\r\nEquinis refers to a deformity that affects the hindfoot, limiting dorsiflexion.\r\n\r\nPes cavus is the opposite of Pes planus, characterized by an excessively high arch.\r\n\r\nLateral deformity is a nonspecific term and does not fit with the symptoms described.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 827.","responses":[{"text":"Club foot","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lateral deformity","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pes cavus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Equinis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pes planus","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":11915,"text":"A patient presents to the emergency room with a fracture of the shaft of the humerus. It is a closed fracture with no observable injury to the radial nerve. What is the best method for stabilizing the bone?","explanation":"The best method for stabilizing a **closed fracture of the shaft of the humerus** with no observable injury to the radial nerve is a **functional brace**. This approach allows for non-surgical management and provides stability while allowing some motion, which is crucial for bone healing and maintaining muscle tone.\r\n\r\nPlate fixation and open reduction are generally more invasive surgical options and are often reserved for complex or open fractures.\r\n\r\nSling could be used for initial stabilization but is not the best method for the definitive treatment of a humeral shaft fracture.\r\n\r\nKocher technique is used for reducing anterior shoulder dislocations, not for treating humeral shaft fractures.","reference":"Dow Lecture slides: Locomotor module, Subject: Orthopaedics, Topic: Management of Fractures \u0026 Dislocations of the Upper Limb, Sub-topic: Fractures Shaft of the Humerus.","responses":[{"text":"Plate fixation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Open reduction","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Functional brace","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Kocher's technique","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sling","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11916,"text":"A patient is on corticosteroid therapy. Which of the following bone disorders can arise due to it?","explanation":"Long-term **use of corticosteroids** can lead to a decrease in bone mineral density, resulting in **osteoporosis**. Corticosteroids inhibit the function of osteoblasts (bone-forming cells) and promote osteoclast activity (bone-resorbing cells), leading to weakened bones that are prone to fractures.\r\n\r\nOsteomyelitis is a bone infection and is not caused by corticosteroid therapy.\r\n\r\nPaget disease involves abnormal bone remodeling and is not induced by corticosteroids.\r\n\r\nOsteosarcoma is a type of bone cancer and is not linked to corticosteroid use.\r\n\r\nOsteocystic fibrosis is not a recognized medical condition related to bone disorders.","reference":"Katzung BG, Kruidering-Hall M, Trevor AJ. Katzung \u0026 Trevor’s Pharmacology Examination \u0026 Board Review. 13th ed. McGraw-Hill Medical; 2021: 334.","responses":[{"text":"Osteomyelitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Osteocystic fibrosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Osteosarcoma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Paget disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Osteoporosis","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":11917,"text":"A 35-year-old pregnant woman has chronic renal disease. Which of the following bone disorders she is likely to develop?","explanation":"In **chronic renal disease**, there is **impaired conversion of vitamin D to its active form**, leading to decreased calcium absorption from the gastrointestinal tract. In adults, especially in a state where there are increased calcium demands like pregnancy, this can result in softening of the bones known as **osteomalacia**.\r\n\r\nPaget bone disease primarily affects older individuals and involves abnormal bone remodeling.\r\n\r\nOsteomyelitis is an infection of the bone and is not directly related to chronic renal disease.\r\n\r\nOsteoporosis involves loss of bone mass and is not directly caused by chronic renal disease.\r\n\r\nRickets is a condition similar to osteomalacia but occurs in children, where the bones are still growing.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Perkins JA, eds. Robbins Basic Pathology. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2018: 330.","responses":[{"text":"Osteomyelitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pagets bone disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Rickets","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Osteoporosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Osteomalacia","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":11918,"text":"Which of the following factors contributes least to the stability of the glenohumeral joint?","explanation":"The **glenohumeral joint** is inherently unstable due to its anatomical structure. The **ball and socket architecture** allows for a wide range of motion, but it provides **less stability compared to other joint types**, such as hinge or pivot joints. Thus, the ball and socket nature contributes least to the stability of the glenohumeral joint.\r\n\r\nThe coracoacromial ligament helps prevent superior displacement of the humeral head.\r\n\r\nThe fibrous capsule provides a boundary for the joint and adds stability.\r\n\r\nThe coracohumeral ligament strengthens the superior part of the capsule.\r\n\r\nGlenohumeral ligaments further add to the stability of the joint by connecting the humerus to the glenoid cavity.","reference":"Drake RL. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 695.","responses":[{"text":"Coracohumeral ligament","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ball and socket","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Glenohumeral ligaments","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Coracoacromial ligament","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Fibrous capsule","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11919,"text":"Fracture of the radial neck may lead to damage to which of the following arteries?","explanation":"The **radial artery** is situated close to the **radial neck**, making it susceptible to injury when a fracture occurs in this region. This artery is an important blood supply to the forearm and hand, and its damage could lead to serious complications including compromised blood flow to the region.\r\n\r\nThe axillary, brachial, and subclavian arteries are more proximally located in the upper limb and are not in close proximity to the radial neck.\r\n\r\nThe ulnar artery runs along the ulna, which is the other bone in the forearm, and is not directly impacted by a radial neck fracture.","reference":"Drake RL. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 772.","responses":[{"text":"Axillary","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ulnar","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Radial","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Subclavian","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Brachial","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11920,"text":"Which structure does not pass deep through the extensor retinaculum?","explanation":"The **tibial nerve** does not pass deep to the **extensor retinaculum**; it runs posteriorly, not anteriorly, with the posterior tibial artery.\r\n\r\nThe extensor digitorum longus tendon, extensor hallucis tendon, anterior tibial artery, and tibialis anterior all pass deep to the extensor retinaculum. These structures are part of the anterior compartment of the leg and are held in place by the extensor retinaculum.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 222, 748, 758-759, 773.","responses":[{"text":"Anterior tibial artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tibial nerve","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Tibialis anterior","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Extensor digitorum longus tendon","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Extensor hallucis tendon","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11922,"text":"Both osteoporosis and osteopenia are the results of a decrease in bone mass. What is the similarity between them?","explanation":"Both **osteoporosis** and **osteopenia** are conditions that are often associated with aging and hormonal changes, particularly in **postmenopausal women**. Reduced estrogen levels after menopause are a common cause of loss of bone mass, making postmenopausal women at higher risk for both conditions. Similarly, senile osteoporosis occurs due to aging-related factors.\r\n\r\nMosaic pattern histology is not a common feature of either condition.\r\n\r\nMost cases of osteoporosis and osteopenia are primary rather than secondary.\r\n\r\nSenile high turnover variant is not a shared feature of both conditions.\r\n\r\nThe criterion of \"bone mass at least 2.5 standard deviations below the mean peak bone mass\" is specific to osteoporosis, not osteopenia. Osteopenia is defined as bone density that is lower than normal peak density but not low enough to be classified as osteoporosis.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Perkins JA, eds. Robbins Basic Pathology. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2018: 801-802.","responses":[{"text":"Mosaic pattern histology","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Both are bone mass at least 2.5 standard deviations below the mean peak bone mass","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"The most common causes are senile and post menopause","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Senile high turnover variant","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Most cases are secondary","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11923,"text":"What type of junctional complexes are present between 2 osteocytic processes?","explanation":"**Gap junctions** are specialized **intercellular connections** that allow for direct communication between the cytoplasm of two cells, facilitating the transfer of ions and small molecules. They are essential in tissues that require rapid communication between cells, including in bone among **osteocytes**.\r\n\r\nMacula adherens and desmosomes both serve to adhere cells to one another but don't facilitate direct cellular communication.\r\n\r\nTight junctions create a barrier to prevent leakage of extracellular fluid but also don't allow for direct intercellular communication.\r\n\r\nZonula adherens is another adhesive junction but does not allow for the transfer of ions and small molecules between cells.","reference":"Mescher AL. Junqueira’s Basic Histology: Text and Atlas. 15th ed. McGraw-Hill Medical; 2018: 142.","responses":[{"text":"Desmosomes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Zonula adherens","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Gap junctions","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Tight junctions","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Macula adherens","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11924,"text":"Damage to the brachial plexus results in an upper limb that is medially rotated and adducted, with the elbow remaining in an extended position. What type of palsy is this?","explanation":"**Erb's palsy** is characterized by an upper limb that is medially rotated, adducted, and with an extended elbow, typically due to an injury to the **upper roots of the brachial plexus (C5 and C6)**.\r\n\r\nWrist drop is generally associated with radial nerve injury and is characterized by loss of wrist extension.\r\n\r\nApe hand usually results from median nerve injury, affecting the ability to oppose the thumb.\r\n\r\nKlumpke's palsy affects the lower roots of the brachial plexus (C8 and T1) and usually presents with a claw-like deformity of the hand.\r\n\r\nClaw hand could result from an ulnar nerve injury, and it involves a specific deformity of the fingers but does not involve shoulder or elbow positioning as described.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 199-200.","responses":[{"text":"Ape hand","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Claw hand","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Erb's palsy","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Wrist drop","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Klumpke's palsy","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11925,"text":"There is a loss of sensation between the first and second toes. It is due to injury to which of the following?","explanation":"Loss of sensation between the **first and second toes** is indicative of an injury to the **deep peroneal nerve**. This nerve provides sensation to this specific area and is also involved in the dorsiflexion of the ankle.\r\n\r\nThe superficial peroneal nerve generally supplies the lateral aspect of the leg and dorsum of the foot, except for the area between the first and second toes.\r\n\r\nThe tibial nerve is more associated with plantar flexion and provides sensation to the sole of the foot.\r\n\r\nThe sural nerve provides sensation to the lateral aspect of the lower leg and foot.\r\n\r\nThe common peroneal nerve is a higher nerve that branches into the deep and superficial peroneal nerves; injury to it could cause a more extensive loss of function and sensation.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 697.","responses":[{"text":"Superficial peroneal nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Common peroneal nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sural nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tibial nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Deep peroneal nerve","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":11926,"text":"Which of the following approaches should be used by a physician when interacting with patients?","explanation":"**Empathy** is the ability to understand another person's feelings and perspectives. This quality is essential for healthcare providers as it fosters better patient-doctor communication and often leads to **improved patient outcomes**.\r\n\r\nPathetic approach is not a term generally used in medical contexts and does not foster a healthy patient-doctor relationship. The judgmental approach could harm the patient-doctor relationship, as patients may feel judged and therefore less willing to share important information. A sympathetic approach, while better than being judgmental or apathetic, is not as effective as being empathetic. It involves feeling sorry for the patient rather than understanding their perspective. Apathetic approach suggests a lack of interest or concern, which is not conducive to good medical care.","reference":"Le T, Bhushan V. First Aid for the USMLE Step 1 2022. 32nd ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2022: 271.","responses":[{"text":"Apathetic approach","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pathetic approach","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Judgmental approach","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sympathetic approach","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Empathetic approach","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":11927,"text":"A 25-year-old woman comes to the clinic and is requesting to terminate her pregnancy. What would be the best approach to deal with her concerns?","explanation":"In medical practice, it is essential to prioritize the **patient's autonomy** and to provide unbiased, evidence-based information. The patient should be given the information she needs to make an **informed decision** about her own body.\r\n\r\nCalling her parents or guardians could violate the patient's privacy and autonomy without her explicit consent. Not responding would be neglectful and is not a proper course of action. Telling her it is against her religion imposes your beliefs on the patient and is not ethically acceptable. Telling her it is against your religion lets your personal beliefs interfere with providing evidence-based medical care, which is also not ethically acceptable.","reference":"Le T, Bhushan V. First Aid for the USMLE Step 1 2022. 32nd ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2022: 274.","responses":[{"text":"Do not impose your beliefs or views on her","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Tell her it is against your religion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tell her it is against her religion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Do not respond","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Call her parents or guardians","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11928,"text":"In a clinical setting, which of the following is true for a patient?","explanation":"In a clinical setting, a patient has the right to **withdraw consent at any point** during the treatment process, even after initially giving consent. It is a fundamental aspect of **patient autonomy** and medical ethics.\r\n\r\nConsent is a personal choice and cannot be forced or delegated under normal circumstances. It is a cornerstone of ethical medical practice.","reference":"Le T, Bhushan V. First Aid for the USMLE Step 1 2022. 32nd ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2022: 269.","responses":[{"text":"Consent would not matter","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Can withdraw from consent anytime","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Cannot withdraw from consent after treatment","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Has to give consent under every circumstance","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Has to ask someone else for consent","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11929,"text":"Which structure is damaged in Klumpke's paralysis?","explanation":"**Klumpke's paralysis** is a form of **brachial plexus injury** that affects the lower roots, specifically **C8 and T1**. This leads to weakness or paralysis in the muscles controlling the wrist and hand. It is commonly caused by excessive stretching of the arm, often seen in difficult childbirth or trauma.\r\n\r\nThe radial nerve and musculocutaneous nerve are branches of the brachial plexus but are not the main structures damaged in Klumpke's paralysis. The sacral plexus is related to the lower extremities and has no involvement in this condition. The median nerve is another nerve of the upper extremity but is not specifically implicated in Klumpke's paralysis.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 200.","responses":[{"text":"Brachial plexus","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Sacral plexus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Musculocutaneous nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Radial nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Median nerve","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11930,"text":"A patient presents to the emergency room with a fracture to his femur. Which of the following muscles does not attach to the femur?","explanation":"The **gracilis muscle** originates from the **external point of the ischiopubic ramus** and inserts into the **upper part of the medial surface of the tibia**, not the femur. \r\n\r\nThe other muscles, such as vastus medialis, vastus lateralis, adductor brevis, and adductor longus, all have attachments to the femur. These muscles are involved in various movements of the hip and knee.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 705, 708.","responses":[{"text":"Gracillis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Vastus medialis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Adductor brevis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Vastus lateralis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Adductor longus","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11931,"text":"Which type of cartilage is the most likely to be calcified?","explanation":"**Hyaline cartilage** is the most likely to be calcified. This type of cartilage is the most abundant and is prone to **calcification**, particularly with aging or in the setting of certain diseases. The other types of cartilage are generally less susceptible to calcification.","reference":"Mescher AL. Junqueira’s Basic Histology: Text and Atlas. 15th ed. McGraw-Hill Medical; 2018: 132.","responses":[{"text":"Elastic","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mixed","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Articular","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Fibrocartilage","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hyaline","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":11933,"text":"Which is correct for skeletal muscle?","explanation":"In skeletal muscle cells, also known as muscle fibers, the **T-tubules (transverse tubules)** are invaginations of the cell membrane (sarcolemma) that penetrate deep into the muscle fiber. These T-tubules play a crucial role in muscle contraction. When an **action potential** is generated at the neuromuscular junction, it travels along the sarcolemma and into the T-tubules. This action potential then rapidly spreads throughout the muscle fiber via the T-tubules, ensuring that all parts of the muscle fiber receive the signal simultaneously.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nThe Ca²⁺-calmodulin complex primarily interacts with smooth muscle, not skeletal muscle.\r\n\r\nThe sarcoplasmic reticulum stores and releases calcium ions (Ca²⁺) needed for muscle contraction but does not provide ATP.\r\n\r\nMitochondria are responsible for producing ATP, not for storing Ca²⁺.\r\n\r\nSkeletal muscles do have cross-striations, which are a characteristic feature of their structure.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 81-82.","responses":[{"text":"Sarcoplasmic reticulum provides ATP","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"They do not have cross-striations","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mitochondria are a store house of Ca⁺²","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"T-tubule transfers action potential to the center of muscle fibers","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Ca⁺²-calmodulin complex binds to actin filament","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11941,"text":"What is the most common treatable cause of visual impairment in old age?","explanation":"The most common treatable cause of **visual impairment** in old age is **senile cataracts**. Cataracts can often be surgically removed, and vision can be restored through this procedure, making it a treatable condition.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nGlaucoma is a significant cause of visual impairment but is generally less reversible than cataracts.\r\nMacular degeneration primarily affects central vision and is not readily treatable.\r\nHypertensive retinopathy and diabetic retinopathy are also causes but are often less immediately reversible than cataracts.","reference":"Penman ID, Ralston S, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 24th ed. Elsevier; 2022: 1174.","responses":[{"text":"Macular degeneration","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Glaucoma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Diabetic retinopathy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypertensive retinopathy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Senile cataracts","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":11942,"text":"Which of the following vaccines should be given to the elderly?","explanation":"**Influenza vaccine** is the vaccine most commonly recommended for the elderly individuals.\r\n\r\nMMR (measles, mumps, rubella) is generally not given to the elderly unless there is a specific indication.\r\n\r\nBCG (Bacillus Calmette-Guerin) is primarily used for tuberculosis and is administered at birth.\r\n\r\nHIV vaccine is still under development.\r\n\r\nHepatitis B vaccine could be considered for elderly individuals who are at high risk, but it is not generally recommended for all elderly people.","reference":"Penman ID, Ralston S, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 24th ed. Elsevier; 2022: 241.","responses":[{"text":"Influenza","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"MMR","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"BCG","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"HIV","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hepatitis B","correct":false,"visible":false}]}
]

